```json
{
  "role": "technical-support-engineer",
  "department": "support",
  "scores": {
    "philosophy_depth": 2,
    "handoff_specificity": 5,
    "anti_pattern_quality": 2,
    "ai_deployment_clarity": 5,
    "story_portal_relevance": 4
  },
  "findings": [
    {
      "dimension": "philosophy_depth",
      "score": 2,
      "finding": "All 6 principles are generic platitudes that could apply to any technical role in any company. 'Deep Investigation: Find the real cause' and 'User-Centric Solution: Solve for the user' are one-sentence non-principles that provide zero behavioral guidance. None reference Story Portal's domain (audio recording, media processing), Tier 2/3 escalation dynamics, or the human-AI collaboration model this Hybrid role depends on.",
      "example_rewrite": "| **Reproduce Before You Report** | Never escalate a bug to Engineering without a confirmed, documented reproduction path — if you can't reproduce it in staging, you don't understand it yet. | | **Audio-First Triage** | On Story Portal, 80% of user pain lives in the record→upload→playback chain. Always trace the audio capture API call stack before assuming platform or auth failure. | | **Workaround Is Not a Resolution** | Closing a ticket with a workaround requires a simultaneous bug report filed to Engineering with severity rated — workarounds that die in tickets become recurring Tier 1 escalations. | | **Escalate Evidence, Not Speculation** | When handing off to Engineering, deliver log excerpts, reproduction steps, and affected user count — never escalate a feeling that something is broken. | | **Tier 1 Deflection Debt** | Every time you resolve an issue Tier 1 should have handled, you must produce a knowledge article or training note — otherwise you are subsidizing a skill gap, not eliminating it. | | **Human Judgment Gates AI Pattern Matching** | AI can surface similar past tickets and suggest root causes; the human TSE must validate before any workaround is communicated to users — AI suggestions are hypotheses, not verdicts. |"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "handoff_specificity",
      "score": 5,
      "finding": "Handoff tables name roles and artifact types, which is a partial pass. However, artifacts lack format and content specificity — 'Bug reports' could mean a Slack message or a structured Jira ticket. There is no mention of what fields a bug report must contain, what template a knowledge article follows, or what SLA triggers a handoff versus continued investigation. The 'Monitoring' source in Receives From is not a role — it is a system, and likely not defined in the charter. 'Support Operations Manager' and 'Knowledge Base Manager' need verification against the charter.",
      "example_rewrite": "| Delivers To | Artifact | Format | Required Fields | Trigger | | Engineering | Bug Report | Jira ticket via [Bug Report Template] | Title, affected component (e.g. audio-capture-api), reproduction steps (numbered), affected user count, severity (P1–P4), log excerpts attached | Bug confirmed with reproduction | | Knowledge Base Manager | Technical Resolution Article | Confluence draft using [KBA Template] | Problem statement, root cause, step-by-step resolution, applicable Story Portal version, related bug ticket ID | Issue resolved and not previously documented | | Customer Support Specialist | Ticket Resolution Summary | Comment on originating Zendesk ticket | Resolution method, workaround if applicable, user communication script | Issue closed or workaround delivered |"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "anti_pattern_quality",
      "score": 2,
      "finding": "The role has no dedicated Anti-Patterns section — the template checklist explicitly requires 3–5 role-specific anti-patterns, and they are entirely absent. The DO/DON'T boundary list exists but contains only jurisdictional rules ('don't fix production code') rather than behavioral failure modes that a TSE or AI agent would actually fall into. There is no STOP point around premature escalation, over-reliance on AI pattern matching, or skipping reproduction before bug submission — all real failure modes for this role.",
      "example_rewrite": "## Anti-Patterns to Avoid | Anti-Pattern | Why It's Harmful | Correct Behavior | | **Escalating Unverified Bugs** | Engineering deprioritizes TSE reports when they lack reproduction steps — credibility erodes and real bugs get ignored. | Confirm reproduction in a controlled environment before filing. Every Jira ticket must include numbered repro steps. | | **Closing Tickets with Workarounds Silently** | Users return with the same issue; Tier 1 re-escalates; no systemic fix is ever filed. | Every workaround closure requires a simultaneous P3/P4 bug report filed to Engineering. | | **Treating AI-Suggested Similar Issues as Confirmed Matches** | Audio sync errors in v2.1 may look identical to v2.3 errors but have different root causes — pattern-matching shortcuts lead to wrong fixes. | AI suggestions are starting hypotheses. Human must validate against current logs before acting. | | **Skipping Tier 1 Knowledge Transfer After Resolution** | TSE becomes a permanent escalation dependency; Tier 1 skill gap widens; TSE throughput degrades. | Every resolved Tier 2/3 issue produces either a KBA update or a training note delivered to Customer Support Specialist. | | **Investigating Without Scoping Impact First** | Spending 4 hours on a single-user cosmetic bug while a 200-user audio capture outage sits in queue. | First step of every investigation is user impact count and severity classification before time is invested. |"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "ai_deployment_clarity",
      "score": 5,
      "finding": "The Deployment Notes section describes the Hybrid split at a concept level but gives an AI agent no operational clarity. The iteration protocol is a generic loop with no domain-specific triggers. The Context Requirements section contains unfilled placeholder text ('[Context item 1]', '[Context item 2]') and a skill-loading table with no actual entries — these are template artifacts that were never completed. An AI agent loading this role cannot determine what context files to load, what its first action is on receiving an escalated ticket, or when it must stop and wait versus proceed.",
      "example_rewrite": "### Required Context | Context File | When to Load | | story-portal-audio-api.md | Load on any ticket involving recording, capture failure, or upload timeout | | story-portal-known-issues.md | Load at start of every investigation session | | engineering-bug-severity-rubric.md | Load before filing any bug report | | tier1-escalation-criteria.md | Load when receiving escalation from Customer Support Specialist | ### AI Operating Boundaries in Hybrid Mode - AI MAY: Analyze log excerpts and surface error patterns, draft bug report fields for human review, suggest similar resolved tickets, generate KBA drafts from human-provided resolution notes. - AI MUST STOP AND WAIT: Before communicating any resolution or workaround to a user, before setting bug severity above P3, before marking a ticket resolved, before any direct interaction with Engineering. - AI MUST NOT: Independently close tickets, independently set P1/P2 severity, access production databases without human-initiated session."
    },
    {
      "dimension": "story_portal_relevance",
      "score": 4,
      "finding": "The Story Portal appendix names the right product domains (audio recording, sync/upload, platform stability) but provides no actionable technical specificity. Listing 'Audio capture API' as a component with 'Recording troubleshooting' as knowledge is circular — it tells the agent nothing it couldn't infer from the role name. There are no known failure signatures, no version-specific issues, no environment details (mobile vs. web, iOS vs. Android), no specific error codes, and no indication of what 'Tier 2/3' means in Story Portal's specific escalation context. The priority table is a ranked list with no thresholds or criteria.",
      "example_rewrite": "### Story Portal Technical Specifics | Component | Common Failure Signatures | Investigation Entry Point | Escalation Threshold | | Audio Capture API | 'RecordingSessionTimeout' error after 45s on iOS 17+; corrupted .wav headers on Android low-memory devices | Check client SDK version first; compare against known-issues.md v2.1–v2.3 matrix | Escalate to Engineering if reproducible on SDK ≥ 2.3 with clean headers | | Media Upload System | Multipart upload stalls at 67% on files >100MB; 502 errors correlate with CDN region us-east-1 degradation | Query upload_sessions table for stuck status; cross-reference with SRE monitoring dashboard | Escalate to SRE if >3 users in same region within 1 hour | | User Authentication | Token refresh failures after password reset — affects SSO users only, not email/password accounts | Check auth_events log for 'refresh_token_invalid' within 10 min of password_reset event | Standard P3 bug report to Engineering unless >50 affected users → P2 |"
    }
  ],
  "top_improvement": "Complete the Anti-Patterns section — it is entirely absent and is a mandatory template requirement. A TSE role operating with AI assistance in a Hybrid model is especially vulnerable to specific failure modes (premature escalation, over-trusting AI pattern matching, closing with workarounds silently) that have no guardrails anywhere in this document. This is the highest-risk gap because the absence of anti-patterns means both the human operator and the AI agent have no behavioral correction mechanism built into the role definition."
}
```
